Elimino dal testo: - Stopwords - Numeri - Hashtag o altri caratteri speciali - Le keyword usate per la ricerca

stopwords <- as.data.frame(stopwords(language = "it",source = "nltk"))
colnames(stopwords) <- "word"

unnested <- df %>%
unnest_tokens(word, text, token = "tweets") 
## Using `to_lower = TRUE` with `token = 'tweets'` may not preserve URLs.
tidy_tweets <- unnested %>% 
  anti_join(stopwords) %>% 
  filter(nchar(word)>2)%>%

## Joining, by = "word"
Sentiment_Score <- tidy_sentiment  %>%
  group_by(date)%>%
  summarise(DailyScore = sum(SentimentScore)/n())

ggplot(Sentiment_Score, aes(x = date,y=DailyScore)) + 
  geom_line() +
  labs(y = "Sentiment Score",x="Data")+
  scale_x_date(date_minor_breaks = "1 day")

Smoothing della serie

Moving Avarage settimanale appiattisce troppo la serie, provo approccio con decay esponeziale per creare una serie piu reattiva.

smooth <- EMA(Sentiment_Score$DailyScore,n=5,ratio=0.4)
Sentiment_Score$Smooth <- smooth
ggplot(Sentiment_Score, aes(x = date)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = DailyScore), color = "darkred") + 
  geom_line(aes(y = Smooth), color="steelblue") + 
  labs(y = "Sentiment Score",x="Data")+
  scale_x_date(date_minor_breaks = "1 day")

Approccio Econometrico:

train test

totale <- cbind.data.frame(na.omit(
df_Score2 %>% select(date,Anticipation,Joy,vola))
                           
                           ,df_Score$Sentiment)
colnames(totale) <- c("date","Anticipation","Joy","Vola","Sentiment")
totale <- totale %>% 
  mutate(lagAnticipation =lag(Anticipation)) %>%
  mutate(lagJoy =lag(Joy)) %>%
  mutate(lagSentiment =lag(Sentiment))


#Separo gli ultimi 3 giorni per stima out of sample
train <- totale %>% slice(1:35)
test <- totale %>% slice(36:40)
